\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 62. V. spicata} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 10 (1753) ({\i Pseudolysimachium spicatum} (L.) Opiz). Stems 5-60 cm, erect or ascending from a more or less extensive rhizome, usually hairy and glandular. Leaves 20-80 × 3-30 mm, usually shortly petiolate, linear- to ovate-lanceolate, cuneate at base, subentire to crenate, more or less hairy, opposite. Inflorescence up to 30 cm; pedicels usually less than 1 mm, much shorter than bracts. Calyx-segments usually ovate-elliptical, obtuse; corolla 4-8 mm in diameter, blue. Capsule 2-4 × 2-4 mm, emarginate, glabrous; style 4-10 mm.{\i  Dry grassland and rocky slopes. Much of Europe, but rare in the west and absent from most of the islands}. Al Au Br Bu Cz Da Fe Ga Ge He Hs Hu It Ju No Po Rm Rs (N, B, C, W, K, E) Su Tu [Ho]. 
