\pard\f0\fs28   All plants from N. & N.W. Europe hitherto investigated are tetraploid, but diploid plants are known from C. & S.E. Europe. {\i V. euxina} Turrill,{\i  Jour. Bot.} ({\i London}){\b  63}: 161 (1925), described from Bulgaria, is one of these diploids; it is densely glandular-hairy, with ovate-elliptical, subsessile lower leaves. It is not yet possible to distinguish the diploid taxa satisfactorily from the widespread and variable tetraploids.  
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Natural hybrids between {\b 62}({\b a}) and {\b 59} are found occasionally in districts where both parents grow; they are particularly well-known in the Baltic area. 
